# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ac-induction-motors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] An **induction motor** or **asynchronous motor** is an AC electric motor in which the electric current in the rotor that produces torque is obtained by electromagnetic induction from the magnetic field of the stator winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] An induction motor therefore needs no electrical connections to the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] An induction motor's rotor can be either wound type or squirrel-cage type.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Three-phase squirrel-cage induction motors are widely used as industrial drives because they are self-starting, reliable, and economical.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Single-phase induction motors are used extensively for smaller loads, such as garbage disposals and stationary power tools.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Although traditionally used for constant-speed service, single- and three-phase induction motors are increasingly being installed in variable-speed applications using variable-frequency drives (VFD).
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] VFD offers energy savings opportunities for induction motors in applications like fans, pumps, and compressors that have a variable load.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In 1824, the French physicist François Arago formulated the existence of rotating magnetic fields, termed Arago's rotations.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] By manually turning switches on and off, Walter Baily demonstrated this in 1879, effectively the first primitive induction motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The first commutator-free single-phase AC induction motor was invented by Hungarian engineer Ottó Bláthy; he used the single-phase motor to propel his invention, the electricity meter.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The first AC commutator-free polyphase induction motors were independently invented by Galileo Ferraris and Nikola Tesla, a working motor model having been demonstrated by the former in 1885 and by the latter in 1887.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Tesla applied for US patents in October and November 1887 and was granted some of these patents in May 1888.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In April 1888, the *Royal Academy of Science of Turin* published Ferraris's research on his AC polyphase motor detailing the foundations of motor operation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] George Westinghouse, who was developing an alternating current power system at that time, licensed Tesla's patents in 1888 and purchased a US patent option on Ferraris' induction motor concept.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Tesla was also employed for one year as a consultant.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Scott was assigned to assist Tesla and later took over development of the induction motor at Westinghouse.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Steadfast in his promotion of three-phase development, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky invented the cage-rotor induction motor in 1889 and the three-limb transformer in 1890.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Furthermore, he claimed that Tesla's motor was not practical because of two-phase pulsations, which prompted him to persist in his three-phase work.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Although Westinghouse achieved its first practical induction motor in 1892 and developed a line of polyphase 60 hertz induction motors in 1893, these early Westinghouse motors were two-phase motors with wound rotors until B.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Lamme developed a rotating bar winding rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The General Electric Company (GE) began developing three-phase induction motors in 1891.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] By 1896, General Electric and Westinghouse signed a cross-licensing agreement for the bar-winding-rotor design, later called the squirrel-cage rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Kennelly was the first to bring out the full significance of complex numbers (using *j* to represent the square root of minus one) to designate the 90º rotation operator in analysis of AC problems.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] GE's Charles Proteus Steinmetz improved the application of AC complex quantities and developed an analytical model called the induction motor Steinmetz equivalent circuit.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Induction motor improvements flowing from these inventions and innovations were such that a 100-horsepower induction motor built in the 1970s had the same mounting dimensions as a 7.5-horsepower motor in 1897.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In both induction and synchronous motors, the AC power supplied to the motor's stator creates a magnetic field that rotates in synchronism with the AC oscillations.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Whereas a synchronous motor's rotor turns at the same rate as the stator field, an induction motor's rotor rotates at a somewhat slower speed than the stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The induction motor's stator magnetic field is therefore changing or rotating relative to the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] This induces an opposing current in the rotor, in effect the motor's secondary winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The rotating magnetic flux induces currents in the rotor windings, in a manner similar to currents induced in a transformer's secondary winding(s).
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The induced currents in the rotor windings in turn create magnetic fields in the rotor that react against the stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The direction of the rotor magnetic field opposes the change in current through the rotor windings, following Lenz's Law.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The cause of induced current in the rotor windings is the rotating stator magnetic field, so to oppose the change in rotor-winding currents the rotor turns in the direction of the stator magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The rotor accelerates until the magnitude of induced rotor current and torque balances the load on the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Since rotation at synchronous speed does not induce rotor current, an induction motor always operates slightly slower than synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The difference, or "slip," between actual and synchronous speed varies from about 0.5% to 5.0% for standard Design B torque curve induction motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The induction motor's essential character is that torque is created solely by induction instead of the rotor being separately excited as in synchronous or DC machines or being self-magnetized as in permanent magnet motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] For rotor currents to be induced, the speed of the physical rotor must be either slower or faster than that of the stator's rotating magnetic field ( $n_{s}$ ); otherwise the magnetic field would not be moving relative to the rotor conductors and no currents would be induced.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] As the speed of the rotor drops below synchronous speed, the rotation rate of the magnetic field in the rotor increases, inducing more current in the windings and creating more torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The ratio between the rotation rate of the magnetic field induced in the rotor and the rotation rate of the stator's rotating field is called "slip".
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Under load, the speed drops and the slip increases enough to create sufficient torque to turn the load.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] For this reason, induction motors are sometimes referred to as "asynchronous motors".
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] An induction motor can be used as an induction generator, or it can be unrolled to form a linear induction motor which can directly generate linear motion.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The generating mode for induction motors is complicated by the need to excite the rotor, which begins with only residual magnetization.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In some cases, that residual magnetization is enough to self-excite the motor under load.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Therefore, it is necessary to either snap the motor and connect it momentarily to a live grid or to add capacitors charged initially by residual magnetism and providing the required reactive power during operation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Similar is the operation of the induction motor in parallel with a synchronous motor serving as a power factor compensator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A feature in the generator mode in parallel to the grid is that the rotor speed is higher than in the driving mode.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Then active energy is being given to the grid.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Another disadvantage of the induction motor generator is that it consumes a significant magnetizing current **I**0 = (20–35)%.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] An AC motor's synchronous speed, $f_{s}$ , is the rotation rate of the stator's magnetic field $f_{s}={2f \over p},$ where f is the frequency of the power supply in hertz and p is the number of magnetic poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The number of magnetic poles, p , is the number of north and south poles per phase.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] For example; a single-phase motor with 3 north and 3 south poles, having 6 poles per phase, is a 6-pole motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A three-phase motor with 18 north and 18 south poles, having 6 poles per phase, is also a 6-pole motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] This industry standard method of counting poles results in the same synchronous speed for a given frequency regardless of polarity.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Slip, s , is defined as the difference between synchronous speed and operating speed, at the same frequency, expressed in rpm, or in percentage or ratio of synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] where $n_{s}$ is stator electrical speed, $n_{r}$ is rotor electrical speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The equation is correct for small and moderate amounts of slip, but not for large amounts of slip, such as a stopped rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Double revolving field theory in the next section, provides a better approximation to actual torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Slip, which varies from zero at synchronous speed and 1 when the rotor is stalled, influences the motor's torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Because the short-circuited rotor windings have small resistance, even a small slip induces a large current in the rotor and produces significant torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] At full rated load, slip varies from more than 5% for small or special purpose motors to less than 1% for large motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] These speed variations can cause load-sharing problems when differently sized motors are mechanically connected.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Various methods are available to reduce slip, VFDs often offering the best solution.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The rotor of an induction motor is subject to two rotating magnet fields, which rotate in opposite directions.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Torque is the result of the difference between these two rotating fields.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The illustration shows torque as a function of slip.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The green line shows torque developed by a single-phase induction motor, without a starting winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] No torque is developed when the rotor is stopped.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A slight push in either direction will cause the rotor to accelerate in the direction that it was pushed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Torque is on the vertical axis shown as a green line, and slip is on the horizontal axis.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Slip ranges from zero to zero, corresponding to the reverse and forward directions of the rotor, with 1.0 slip in the center as the point where the rotor is stopped and no torque is produced.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Torque is the net result of two counter-rotating magnetic fields, with one shown as a blue line, and the other shown as a red line.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The red and blue lines are mirror images of the typical torque curve shown in the previous section.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The typical speed-torque relationship of a standard NEMA Design B polyphase induction motor is as shown in the curve at right.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Over a motor's normal load range, the torque's slope is approximately linear or proportional to slip because the value of rotor resistance divided by slip, $R_{r}'/s$ , dominates torque in a linear manner.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] As load increases above rated load, stator and rotor leakage reactance factors gradually become more significant in relation to $R_{r}'/s$ such that torque gradually curves towards breakdown torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] As the load torque increases beyond breakdown torque the motor stalls.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] There are three basic types of small induction motors: split-phase single-phase, shaded-pole single-phase, and polyphase.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In two-pole single-phase motors, the torque goes to zero at 100% slip (zero speed), so these require alterations to the stator such as shaded-poles to provide starting torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A single phase induction motor requires separate starting circuitry to provide a rotating field to the motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The normal running windings within such a single-phase motor can cause the rotor to turn in either direction, so the starting circuit determines the operating direction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In certain smaller single-phase motors, starting is done by means of a copper wire turn around part of a pole; such a pole is referred to as a shaded pole.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The current induced in this turn lags behind the supply current, creating a delayed magnetic field around the shaded part of the pole face.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] This imparts sufficient rotational field energy to start the motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] These motors are typically used in applications such as desk fans and record players, as the required starting torque is low, and the low efficiency is tolerable relative to the reduced cost of the motor and starting method compared to other AC motor designs.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Larger single phase motors are split-phase motors and have a second stator winding fed with out-of-phase current; such currents may be created by feeding the winding through a capacitor or having it receive different values of inductance and resistance from the main winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The *capacitor-run* designs keep the second winding on when running, improving torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A *resistance start* design uses a starter inserted in series with the startup winding, creating reactance.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Self-starting polyphase induction motors produce torque even at standstill.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Available squirrel-cage induction motor starting methods include direct-on-line starting, reduced-voltage reactor or auto-transformer starting, star-delta starting or, increasingly, new solid-state soft assemblies and, of course, variable frequency drives (VFDs).
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Polyphase motors have rotor bars shaped to give different speed-torque characteristics.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The current distribution within the rotor bars varies depending on the frequency of the induced current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] At standstill, the rotor current is the same frequency as the stator current, and tends to travel at the outermost parts of the cage rotor bars (by skin effect).
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The different bar shapes can give usefully different speed-torque characteristics as well as some control over the inrush current at startup.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Although polyphase motors are inherently self-starting, their starting and pull-up torque design limits must be high enough to overcome actual load conditions.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In wound rotor motors, rotor circuit connection through slip rings to external resistances allows change of speed-torque characteristics for acceleration control and speed control purposes.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Before the development of semiconductor power electronics, it was difficult to vary the frequency, and cage induction motors were mainly used in fixed speed applications.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Applications, such as electric overhead cranes, used DC drives or wound rotor motors (WRIM) with slip rings for rotor circuit connection to variable external resistance allowing considerable range of speed control.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] However, resistor losses associated with low speed operation of WRIMs is a major cost disadvantage, especially for constant loads.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Large slip ring motor drives, termed slip energy recovery systems, some still in use, recover energy from the rotor circuit, rectify it, and return it to the power system using a VFD.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The speed of a pair of slip-ring motors can be controlled by a cascade connection, or concatenation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The rotor of one motor is connected to the stator of the other.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] If the two motors are also mechanically connected, they will run at half speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] This system was once widely used in three-phase AC railway locomotives, such as FS Class E.333.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] By the turn of this century, however, such cascade-based electromechanical systems became much more efficiently and economically solved using power semiconductor elements solutions.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In many industrial variable-speed applications, DC and WRIM drives are being displaced by VFD-fed cage induction motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The most common efficient way to control asynchronous motor speed of many loads is with VFDs.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Barriers to adoption of VFDs due to cost and reliability considerations have been reduced considerably over the past three decades such that it is estimated that drive technology is adopted in as many as 30–40% of all newly installed motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Variable frequency drives implement the scalar or vector control of an induction motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] With scalar control, only the magnitude and frequency of the supply voltage are controlled without phase control (absent feedback by rotor position).
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Scalar control is suitable for application where the load is constant.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Vector control allows independent control of the speed and torque of the motor, making it possible to maintain a constant rotation speed at varying load torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] But vector control is more expensive because of the cost of the sensor (not always) and the requirement for a more powerful controller.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The stator of an induction motor consists of poles carrying supply current to induce a magnetic field that penetrates the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] To optimize the distribution of the magnetic field, windings are distributed in slots around the stator, with the magnetic field having the same number of north and south poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Induction motors are most commonly run on single-phase or three-phase power, but two-phase motors exist; in theory, induction motors can have any number of phases.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Many single-phase motors having two windings can be viewed as two-phase motors, since a capacitor is used to generate a second power phase 90° from the single-phase supply and feeds it to the second motor winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Single-phase motors require some mechanism to produce a rotating field on startup.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Induction motors using a squirrel-cage rotor winding may have the rotor bars skewed slightly to smooth out torque in each revolution.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Standardized NEMA & IEC motor frame sizes throughout the industry result in interchangeable dimensions for shaft, foot mounting, general aspects as well as certain motor flange aspect.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Since an open drip proof (ODP) motor design allows a free air exchange from outside to the inner stator windings, this style of motor tends to be slightly more efficient because the windings are cooler.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] At a given power rating, lower speed requires a larger frame.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The method of changing the direction of rotation of an induction motor depends on whether it is a three-phase or single-phase machine.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A three-phase motor can be reversed by swapping any two of its phase connections.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Motors required to change direction regularly (such as hoists) will have extra switching contacts in their controller to reverse rotation as needed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] A variable frequency drive nearly always permits reversal by electronically changing the phase sequence of voltage applied to the motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] In a single-phase split-phase motor, reversal is achieved by reversing the connections of the starting winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Some motors bring out the start winding connections to allow selection of rotation direction at installation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] If the start winding is permanently connected within the motor, it is impractical to reverse the sense of rotation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Single-phase shaded-pole motors have a fixed rotation unless a second set of shading windings is provided.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The power factor of induction motors varies with load, typically from about 0.85 or 0.90 at full load to as low as about 0.20 at no-load, due to stator and rotor leakage and magnetizing reactances.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Power factor can be improved by connecting capacitors either on an individual motor basis or, by preference, on a common bus covering several motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] For economic and other considerations, power systems are rarely power factor corrected to unity power factor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Power capacitor application with harmonic currents requires power system analysis to avoid harmonic resonance between capacitors and transformer and circuit reactances.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Common bus power factor correction is recommended to minimize resonant risk and to simplify power system analysis.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Regulatory authorities in many countries have implemented legislation to encourage the manufacture and use of higher efficiency electric motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Some legislation mandates the future use of premium-efficiency induction motors in certain equipment.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The equivalent circuit is a single-phase representation of a multiphase induction motor that is valid in steady-state balanced-load conditions.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Paraphrasing from Alger in Knowlton, an induction motor is simply an electrical transformer the magnetic circuit of which is separated by an air gap between the stator winding and the moving rotor winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] The equivalent circuit can accordingly be shown either with equivalent circuit components of respective windings separated by an ideal transformer or with rotor components referred to the stator side as shown in the following circuit and associated equation and parameter definition tables.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Linear induction motors, which work on the same general principles as rotary induction motors (frequently three-phase), are designed to produce straight line motion.
[src:ac-induction-motors/induction-motor] Uses include magnetic levitation, linear propulsion, linear actuators, and liquid metal pumping.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] A **rotating magnetic field (RMF)** is the resultant magnetic field produced by a system of coils symmetrically placed and supplied with polyphase currents.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] A rotating magnetic field can be produced by a poly-phase (two or more phases) current or by a single phase current provided that, in the latter case, two field windings are supplied and are so designed that the two resulting magnetic fields generated thereby are out of phase.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Rotating magnetic fields are often utilized for electromechanical applications, such as induction motors, electric generators and induction regulators.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] In 1879, English physicist Walter Baily replaced the horseshoe magnets with four electromagnets and, by manually turning switches on and off, demonstrated a primitive induction motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The idea of a rotating magnetic field in an AC motor was explored by the Italian physicist and electrical engineer Galileo Ferraris and the Serbian-American inventor and electrical engineer Nikola Tesla.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Ferraris, who did research about the theory and design of alternating-current machinery, built a working model for a classroom demonstration in 1885, but did not describe it publicly until 1888.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Tesla attempted several (unsuccessful) designs and working models through the early 1880s before building a working prototype in 1887 According to Ferraris principle of rotating magnetic field, Friedrich August Haselwander developed the first AC 3 phase generator in 1887.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] In 1888, Ferraris published his research in a paper to the *Royal Academy of Sciences* in Turin and Tesla obtained a United States patent (U.S. patent 0,381,968) for his design.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Based on the Haselwander generator, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky developed a three-phase generator and motor for the world's first three-phase power plant built in 1891 in Frankfurt, Germany.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The rotating magnetic field is the key principle in the operation of induction machines.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The induction motor consists of a stator and rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] In the stator a group of fixed windings are so arranged that a two phase current, for example, produces a magnetic field which rotates at an angular velocity determined by the frequency of the alternating current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The rotor or armature consists of coils wound in slots, which are short circuited and in which the changing flux generated by the field poles induce a current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The flux generated by the armature current reacts upon the field poles and the armature is set in rotation in a definite direction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] A symmetric rotating magnetic field can be produced with as few as two polar wound coils driven at 90-degree phasing.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] However, three sets of coils are nearly always used, because it is compatible with a symmetric three-phase AC sine current system.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The three coils are driven with each set 120 degrees in phase from the others.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] For the purpose of this example, the magnetic field is taken to be the linear function of the coil's current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The result of adding three 120-degree phased sine waves on the axis of the motor is a single rotating vector that always remains constant in magnitude.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The rotor has a constant magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The north pole of the rotor will move toward the south pole of the magnetic field of the stator, and vice versa.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] This magnetomechanical attraction creates a force that will drive the rotor to follow the rotating magnetic field in a synchronous manner.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] A permanent magnet in such a field will rotate so as to maintain its alignment with the external field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] This effect was utilized in early alternating-current electric motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] A rotating magnetic field can be constructed using two orthogonal coils with a 90-degree phase difference in their alternating currents.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] However, in practice, such a system would be supplied through a three-wire arrangement with unequal currents.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] This inequality would cause serious problems in the standardization of the conductor size.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] In order to overcome this, three-phase systems are used in which the three currents are equal in magnitude and have a 120-degree phase difference.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Three similar coils having mutual geometrical angles of 120 degrees will create the rotating magnetic field in this case.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] The ability of the three-phase system to create the rotating field utilized in electric motors is one of the main reasons why three-phase systems dominate the world's electric power-supply systems.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Rotating magnetic fields are also used in induction motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] Because magnets degrade with time, induction motors use short-circuited rotors (instead of a magnet), which follow the rotating magnetic field of a multicoiled stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] In these motors, the short-circuited turns of the rotor develop eddy currents in the rotating field of the stator, which in turn move the rotor by Lorentz force.
[src:ac-induction-motors/rotating-magnetic-field] These types of motors are not usually synchronous, but instead necessarily involve a degree of 'slip' in order that the current may be produced due to the relative movement of the field and the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] A **squirrel-cage rotor** is the rotating part of the common squirrel-cage induction motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] It consists of a cylinder of steel laminations, with aluminum or copper conductors cast in its surface.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] In operation, the non-rotating stator winding is connected to an alternating current power source; the alternating current in the stator produces a rotating magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The rotor winding has current induced in it by the stator field, as happens in a transformer, except that the current in the rotor is varying at the stator field rotation rate minus the physical rotation rate.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The interaction of the magnetic fields in the stator and the currents in the rotor produce a torque on the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] By adjusting the shape of the bars in the rotor, the speed-torque characteristics of the motor can be changed, to minimize starting current or to maximize low-speed torque, for example.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Squirrel-cage induction motors are very prevalent in industry, in sizes from below 1 kilowatt (1.3 hp) up to tens of megawatts (tens-of-thousand horsepower).
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] They are simple, rugged, and self-starting, and maintain a reasonably constant speed from light load to full load, set by the frequency of the power supply and the number of poles of the stator winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Commonly used motors in industry are usually IEC or NEMA standard frame sizes, which are interchangeable between manufacturers.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] This simplifies application and replacement of these motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Galileo Ferraris described an induction machine with a two-phase stator winding and a solid copper cylindrical armature in 1885.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] In 1888, Nikola Tesla received a patent on a two-phase induction motor with a short-circuited copper rotor winding and a two-phase stator winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Developments of this design became commercially important.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] In 1889, Mikhail Dolivo-Dobrovolsky developed a wound-rotor induction motor, and shortly afterwards a cage-type rotor winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] By the end of the 19th century induction motors were widely applied on the growing alternating-current electrical distribution systems.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The motor rotor shape is a cylinder mounted on a shaft.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Internally it contains longitudinal conductive bars (usually made of aluminium or copper) set into grooves and connected at both ends by shorting rings forming a cage-like shape.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The name is derived from the similarity between this rings-and-bars winding and a squirrel cage.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The solid core of the rotor is built with stacks of electrical steel laminations.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The figure shows three of many lamination sets used.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The rotor lamination has a larger number of slots than its corresponding stator lamination, and the number of rotor slots should be a non-integer multiple of the number of stator slots to prevent magnetic interlocking of rotor and stator teeth at the starting instant.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The rotor bars may be made of either copper or aluminium.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] A very common structure for smaller motors uses die cast aluminium poured into the rotor after the laminations are stacked.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Larger motors have aluminium or copper bars which are welded or brazed to end-rings.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Since the voltage developed in the squirrel cage winding is very low, and the current very high, no intentional insulation layer is present between the bars and the rotor steel.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The field windings in the stator of an induction motor set up a rotating magnetic field through the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The relative motion between this field and the rotor induces electric current in the conductive bars.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] In turn these currents lengthwise in the conductors react with the magnetic field of the motor to produce force acting at a tangent orthogonal to the rotor, resulting in torque to turn the shaft.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] In effect the rotor is carried around with the magnetic field but at a slightly slower rate of rotation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The difference in speed is called *slip* and increases with load.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The conductors are often skewed slightly along the length of the rotor to reduce noise and smooth out torque fluctuations that might result at some speeds due to interactions with the pole pieces of the stator, by ensuring that at any time the same fraction of a rotor bar is under each stator slot.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] If rotor bars were parallel to the stator poles, the motor would experience a drop and then recovery in torque as each bar passes the gap in the stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The laminations shown in the photo have 36 bars in the stator and 40 bars in the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The greatest common divisor of 36 and 40 is 4, with the result that no more than 4 bars of the stator and rotor can be aligned at any one time, which also reduces torque fluctuations.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The number of bars in the rotor determines to what extent the induced currents are fed back to the stator coils and hence the current through them.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The constructions that offer the least feedback use prime numbers of rotor bars.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The iron core serves to carry the magnetic field through the rotor conductors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Because the magnetic field in the rotor is alternating with time, the core uses construction similar to a transformer core to reduce core energy losses.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] It is made of thin laminations, separated by varnish insulation, to reduce eddy currents circulating in the core.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The material is a low carbon but high-silicon iron with several times the resistivity of pure iron, further reducing eddy-current loss, and low coercivity to reduce hysteresis loss.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The same basic design is used for both single-phase and three-phase motors over a wide range of sizes.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Rotors for three-phase will have variations in the depth and shape of bars to suit the design classification.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Generally, thick bars have good torque and are efficient at low slip, since they present lower resistance to the EMF.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] As the slip increases, the skin effect starts to reduce the effective depth and increases the resistance, resulting in reduced efficiency but still maintaining torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The shape and depth of the rotor bars can be used to vary the speed-torque characteristics of the induction motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] At standstill, the revolving magnetic field passes the rotor bars at a high rate, inducing line-frequency current into the rotor bars.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Due to the skin effect, the induced current tends to flow at the outer edge of the winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] As the motor accelerates, the slip frequency decreases and induced current flows at greater depths in the winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] By tapering the profile of the rotor bars to vary their resistance at different depths, or by constructing a double squirrel cage, with a combination of high and low impedance rotor in parallel the motor can be arranged to produce more or less torque at standstill and near its synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] To demonstrate how the cage rotor works, the stator of a single-phase motor and a copper pipe (as rotor) may be used.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] If adequate AC power is applied to the stator, an alternating magnetic field will revolve around within the stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] If the copper pipe is inserted inside the stator, there will be an induced current in the pipe, and this current will produce a magnetic field of its own in the pipe.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The interaction between the stator's revolving magnetic field and the copper-pipe-rotor's induced magnetic field produces a torque and thus rotation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] A synchronous motor may have a squirrel-cage winding embedded in its rotor, used to increase the motor starting torque and so decrease the time to accelerate to synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The squirrel cage winding of a synchronous machine will generally be smaller than for an induction machine of similar rating.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] When the rotor is turning at the same speed as the stator's revolving magnetic field, no current is induced into the squirrel-cage windings and the windings will have no further effect on the operation of the synchronous motor at steady-state.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] The squirrel cage winding in some machines provides a damping effect for load or system disturbances, and in this role may be designated as an amortisseur windings.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Large machines may only have amortisseur bars in the individual pole faces, not interconnected between poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Because the squirrel cage winding is not large enough to dissipate the heat of continuous operation, large synchronous machines often have protective relays to detect when the machine has fallen out of synchronization with the supply voltage.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] Three phase squirrel cage induction motors can also be used as generators.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] For this to work the motor must see a reactive load, and either be connected to a grid supply or an arrangement of capacitors to provide excitation current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] For the motor to work as a generator instead of a motor the rotor must be spun faster than its stator's synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/squirrel-cage-rotor] This will cause the motor to generate power after building up its residual magnetism.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A **synchronous electric motor** is an AC electric motor in which, at steady state, the rotation of the shaft is synchronized with the frequency of the supply current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors use permanent magnets or electromagnets for rotors, and electromagnets for stators.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The stator creates a magnetic field that rotates in time with the oscillations of the current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotor turns in step with the stator field at the same rate and as a result, provides a second synchronized rotating magnet field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous and induction motors are the most widely used AC motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors rotate at a rate locked to the line frequency since they do not rely on induction to produce the rotor's magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Induction motors require *slip*: the rotor must rotate at a frequency slightly slower than the AC alternations in order to induce current in the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors are available in self-excited, fractional to industrial sizes.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In the fractional power range, most synchronous motors are used to provide precise constant speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] These machines are commonly used in analog electric clocks, timers and related devices.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Doubly fed synchronous motors use independently-excited multiphase AC electromagnets for both rotor and stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In typical industrial sizes, the synchronous motor provides an efficient means of converting AC energy to work (electrical efficiency above 95% is normal for larger sizes) and it can operate at leading or unity power factor and thereby provide power-factor correction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous motors fall under the category of *synchronous machines* that also includes synchronous generators.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Generator action occurs if the field poles are "driven ahead of the resultant air-gap flux by the forward motion of the prime mover".
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Motor action occurs if the field poles are "dragged behind the resultant air-gap flux by the retarding torque of a shaft load".
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The two major types of synchronous motors are distinguished by how the rotor is magnetized: non-excited and direct-current excited.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In non-excited motors, the external stator field magnetizes the rotor, inducing the magnetic poles needed to turn the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotor rotates in step with the stator's rotating magnetic field, so it has an almost-constant magnetic field through it.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotor is made of a high-retentivity steel such as cobalt steel.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A permanent-magnet synchronous motor (PMSM) uses permanent magnets embedded in the rotor to create a constant magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The stator carries windings connected to an AC electricity supply to produce a rotating magnetic field (as in an asynchronous motor).
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] At synchronous speed the rotor poles lock to the rotating magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] PMSMs are similar to brushless DC motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Neodymium magnets are the most common, although rapid fluctuation of neodymium magnet prices triggered research in ferrite magnets.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Due to inherent characteristics of ferrite magnets, the magnetic circuit of these machines needs to be able to concentrate the magnetic flux, typically leading to the use of spoke type rotors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Machines that use ferrite magnets have lower power density and torque density when compared with neodymium machines.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] PMSMs have been used as gearless elevator motors since 2000.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Most PMSMs require a variable-frequency drive to start them.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] However, some incorporate a squirrel cage in the rotor for starting—these are known as line-start or self-starting.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] These are typically used as higher-efficiency replacements for induction motors (owing to the lack of slip), but must ensure that synchronous speed is reached and that the system can withstand torque ripple during starting.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] PMSMs are typically controlled using direct torque control and field oriented control.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Reluctance motors have a solid steel cast rotor with projecting (salient) toothed poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Typically there are fewer rotor than stator poles to minimize torque ripple and to prevent the poles from all aligning simultaneously—a position that cannot generate torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The size of the air gap in the magnetic circuit and thus the reluctance is minimum when the poles align with the stator's (rotating) magnetic field, and increases with the angle between them.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This creates torque that pulls the rotor into alignment with the nearest pole of the stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] At synchronous speed the rotor is thus "locked" to the rotating stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This cannot start the motor, so the rotor poles usually have squirrel-cage windings embedded in them, to provide torque below synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The machine thus starts as an induction motor until it approaches synchronous speed, when the rotor "pulls in" and locks to the stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Reluctance motor designs have ratings that range from fractional horsepower (a few watts) to about 22 kW.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Small reluctance motors have low torque, and are generally used for instrumentation applications.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Moderate torque, multi-horsepower motors use squirrel cage construction with toothed rotors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] When used with an adjustable frequency power supply, all motors in a drive system can operate at exactly the same speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The power supply frequency determines motor operating speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Hysteresis motors have a solid, smooth, cylindrical rotor, cast of a high coercivity magnetically "hard" cobalt steel.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This material has a wide hysteresis loop (high coercivity), meaning once it is magnetized in a given direction, it requires a high magnetic field to reverse the magnetization.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotating stator field causes each small volume of the rotor to experience a reversing magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Because of hysteresis the phase of the magnetization lags behind the phase of the applied field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Thus the axis of the magnetic field induced in the rotor lags behind the axis of the stator field by a constant angle δ, producing torque as the rotor tries to "catch up" with the stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] As long as the rotor is below synchronous speed, each particle of the rotor experiences a reversing magnetic field at the "slip" frequency that drives it around its hysteresis loop, causing the rotor field to lag and create torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotor has a 2-pole low reluctance bar structure.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] As the rotor approaches synchronous speed and slip goes to zero, this magnetizes and aligns with the stator field, causing the rotor to "lock" to the rotating stator field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A major advantage of the hysteresis motor is that since the lag angle δ is independent of speed, it develops constant torque from startup to synchronous speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Therefore, it is self-starting and doesn't need an induction winding to start it, although many designs embed a squirrel-cage conductive winding structure in the rotor to provide extra torque at start-up.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Hysteresis motors are manufactured in sub-fractional horsepower ratings, primarily as servomotors and timing motors.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] More expensive than the reluctance type, hysteresis motors are used where precise constant speed is required.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Usually made in larger sizes (larger than about 1 horsepower or 1 kilowatt) these motors require direct current (DC) to excite (magnetize) the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This is most straightforwardly supplied through slip rings.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A brushless AC induction and rectifier arrangement can also be used.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A permanent magnet synchronous motor and reluctance motor requires a control system for operating (VFD or servo drive).
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] There is a large number of control methods for synchronous machines, selected depending on the construction of the electric motor and the scope.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The PMSMs can also operate on open-loop control, which is sometimes used for start-up thus enabling the position sensing operation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A single-phase, 4-pole (2-pole-pair) synchronous motor is operating at an AC supply frequency of 50 Hz.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A three-phase, 12-pole (6-pole-pair) synchronous motor is operating at an AC supply frequency of 60 Hz.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The number of magnetic poles, p , is equal to the number of coil groups per phase.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] To determine the number of coil groups per phase in a 3-phase motor, count the number of coils, divide by the number of phases, which is 3.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The coils may span several slots in the stator core, making it tedious to count them.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] For a 3-phase motor, if you count a total of 12 coil groups, it has 4 magnetic poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] For a 12-pole 3-phase machine, there will be 36 coils.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The number of magnetic poles in the rotor is equal to the number of magnetic poles in the stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The principal components of electric motors are the stator and the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Synchronous motor and induction motor stators are similar in construction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The construction of synchronous motor is similar to that of an alternator (also called synchronous generator).
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The stator frame contains wrapper plate (except for wound-rotor synchronous doubly fed electric machines).
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Circumferential ribs and keybars are attached to the wrapper plate.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] To carry the weight of the machine, frame mounts and footings are required.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The synchronous stator winding consists of a 3 phase winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] It is provided with a 3 phase supply, and the rotor is provided with a DC supply.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] DC excited motors require brushes and slip rings to connect to the excitation supply.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The field winding can be excited by a brushless exciter.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Cylindrical, round rotors, (also known as non-salient pole rotor) are used for up to six poles.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In some machines or when a large number of poles are needed, a salient pole rotor is used.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Most synchronous motor construction uses a stationary armature and rotating field winding.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This type of construction has an advantage over DC motor type where the armature used is of rotating type.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Electric motors generate power due to the interaction of the magnetic fields of the stator and the rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In synchronous motors, the stator carries 3 phase currents and produces 3 phase rotating magnetic flux (and therefore a rotating magnetic field).
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The rotor eventually locks in with the rotating magnetic field and rotates along with it.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Once the rotor field locks in with the rotating magnetic field, the motor is said to be synched.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] A single-phase (or two-phase derived from single phase) stator is possible, but in this case the direction of rotation is not defined and the machine may start in either direction unless prevented from doing so by startup arrangements.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Once the motor is in operation, the speed of the motor is dependent only on the supply frequency.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] When the motor load is increased beyond the breakdown load, the motor falls out of synchronization and the rotor no longer follows the rotating magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Since the motor cannot produce torque if it falls out of synchronization, practical synchronous motors have a partial or complete squirrel-cage damper called an *amortisseur* winding to stabilize operation and facilitate starting.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Above a certain size, synchronous motors cannot self-start.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This property is due to rotor inertia; it cannot instantly follow the rotation of the stator's magnetic field.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Since a synchronous motor produces no inherent average torque at standstill, it cannot accelerate to synchronous speed without a supplemental mechanism.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Large motors operating on commercial power include a squirrel-cage induction winding that provides sufficient torque for acceleration and also serves to damp motor speed oscillations.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Once the rotor nears the synchronous speed, the field winding becomes excited and the motor pulls into synchronization.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Very large motor systems may include a "pony" motor that accelerates the unloaded synchronous machine before load is applied.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Electronically controlled motors can be accelerated from zero speed by changing the frequency of the stator current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Small synchronous motors are commonly used in line-powered electric mechanical clocks or timers that use the power line frequency to run the gear mechanism at the correct speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Such small synchronous motors are able to start without assistance if the moment of inertia of the rotor and its mechanical load are sufficiently small.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The motor accelerates from slip speed to synchronous speed during an accelerating half cycle of the reluctance torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Single-phase synchronous motors such as in electric wall clocks can freely rotate in either direction, unlike a shaded-pole type.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Costs are an important parameter for starters.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Rotor excitation is a possible way to resolve the issue.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In addition, starting methods for large synchronous machines include repetitive polarity inversion of the rotor poles during startup.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] By varying the excitation of a synchronous motor, it can be made to operate at lagging, leading and unity power factor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Excitation at which the power factor is unity is termed *normal excitation voltage*.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The magnitude of current at this excitation is minimum.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Excitation voltage more than normal excitation is called over excitation voltage, excitation voltage less than normal excitation is called under excitation.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] When the motor is over excited, the back emf will be greater than the motor terminal voltage.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This causes a demagnetizing effect due to armature reaction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The V curve of a synchronous machine shows armature current as a function of field current.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] With increasing field current armature current at first decreases, then reaches a minimum, then increases.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The minimum point is also the point at which power factor is unity.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] This ability to selectively control power factor can be exploited for power factor correction of the power system to which the motor is connected.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Since most power systems of any significant size have a net lagging power factor, the presence of overexcited synchronous motors moves the system's net power factor closer to unity, improving efficiency.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] Such power-factor correction is usually a side effect of motors already present in the system to provide mechanical work, although motors can be run without mechanical load simply to provide power-factor correction.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] In large industrial plants such as factories the interaction between synchronous motors and other, lagging, loads may be an explicit consideration in the plant's electrical design.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] When load is applied, torque angle $\delta$ increases.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] When $\delta$ = 90° the torque will be maximum.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] If load is applied further then the motor will lose its synchronism, since motor torque will be less than load torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/synchronous-motor] The maximum load torque that can be applied to a motor without losing its synchronism is called steady state stability limit of a synchronous motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] A **wound-rotor motor**, also known as **slip ring-rotor motor**, is a type of induction motor where the rotor windings are connected through slip rings to external resistance.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Adjusting the resistance allows control of the speed/torque characteristic of the motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Wound-rotor motors can be started with low inrush current, by inserting high resistance into the rotor circuit; as the motor accelerates, the resistance can be decreased.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Compared to a squirrel-cage rotor, the rotor of the slip ring motor has more winding turns; the induced voltage is then higher, and the current lower, than for a squirrel-cage rotor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] During the start-up a typical rotor has 3 poles connected to the slip ring.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Each pole is wired in series with a variable power resistor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] When the motor reaches full speed the rotor poles are switched to short circuit.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] During start-up the resistors reduce the field strength at the stator.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] As a result, the inrush current is reduced.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Another important advantage over squirrel-cage motors is higher starting torque and smooth operation due to variable speed.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] The speed and torque characteristics of a wound-rotor motor can be adjusted by changing the external resistance, unlike a squirrel cage motor which has a fixed characteristic.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] This is useful for speed control of the motor.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] A wound-rotor motor can be used in several forms of adjustable-speed drive.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Common applications include hoists, elevators, and conveyor systems.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Also, the travel mechanism of gantry cranes or overhead cranes also used this type of motor, because it has both adjustable speed and high torque.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Many gantry cranes and portal cranes used in ship yards used this motor for smooth handling of heavy containers, ship handling, ship part handling, because it is very tolerant with overloads and can precisely handle heavy loads, and also its speed is not affected by load.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Certain types of variable-speed drives recover slip-frequency power from the rotor circuit and feed it back to the supply, allowing wide speed range with high energy efficiency.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Doubly-fed electric machines use the slip rings to supply external power to the rotor circuit, allowing wide-range speed control.
[src:ac-induction-motors/wound-rotor-motor] Today speed control by use of slip ring motor is mostly superseded by induction motors with variable-frequency drives.
